My daughter and I went on a quick holiday getaway to explore some Gold rush towns in the Sierras….and on the road home, Monica, my Christmas elf, eyed something special in the snowy banks… we pulled over to the side of the road, she grabbed her saw (doesn’t everybody travel with a saw?!?) and hand cut me a Christmas tree!!! Best tree ever!
My Christmas characters are all lined up and ready to celebrate the holidays!
Happy Winter Solstice!  May your shortest day be full of light!  Nothing makes me happier than a reindeer under the moon!  Lovely photo courtesy of @lindanordvag

We are so very grateful to be here in the magical time and place, and to share our little glimmering world with all of you!

Every year I re-post the remarkable antique Christmas stocking video!  I found this intact stocking at a flea market - it was stuffed with it’s original contents!  This is just the preview - I will post the opening up of this object from the past tonight, Christmas Eve!  It’s like being a child in 1922!!!!
A GIFT FROM CHRISTMAS PAST!!!! Watch to the end as I unwrap the treasures!
A magical peek into CHRISTMAS PAST!!!!

Merry Christmas from our house to yours!  Marcia and I finally got all the decorations up!  It’s cold and foggy out and the perfect time to stay at home, eat too much and spend some quality time with our cats!!!!
Pretty much how I feel after all that turkey!!!

Marcia and I got a Christmas surprise present!  This tiny kitten was abandoned and shivering - hiding under a car tire, on a cold Christmas Eve!  It is now safe, warm and very well fed on turkey!  We are thinking of naming her Jingle!!

Tiny little jingle is getting bigger and fluffier everyday!  My little Christmas Eve gift was found shivering under a car tire - but she is now the life of the household! She is the most affectionate kitten imaginable and purrs when you look at her.  A perfect pal to cuddle with on these foggy cold winter days!  She will be going to the vet soon for a general checkup, but she seems pretty lively!!! P.S.  the ribbon collar was just on for a few minutes!

Hard to convey how tiny little Jingle is!  She won’t stay like this for long.  At the moment she is princess of her domain - the living room - but we will have to slowly introduce her to Smokey and Idgie, our big Maine coon cats, who are used to being the rulers of the house - and the universe in general!  Any suggestions on introducing a new kitten are appreciated!!!

We’ve had weeks of storms and rain here and like magic I awoke this morning to a brilliant blue sky and the world washed clean.  A perfect start to a new year. I’m sending out all my wishes and hopes to all of my friends on Instagram - may 2023 be full of beauty, calmness and joy!
The lights will stay up till at least the end of the month!  I’m not done celebrating…another year of good fortune, the winter outside and the warmth inside, a day of quiet in my magic kingdom.
A few more scenes around the house as I savor the winter day.  My antique curtain has two reindeer embroidered on it!
My kitchen has been put to order!  Napoleon has been a beautiful if haunting presence over my little gas stove for 25 years.
I’m trying to get out of my post Christmas sleep mode…but I have to keep coming back for nap times with Jingle!  Oh well - clean up can wait!

The new year gives me - whether I want it or not - time for reflection. The busy-ness that reaches its yearly crescendo at Christmas time suddenly goes quiet and there is room for all kinds of thoughts and feelings to surface. I know that I am trying, always, with all my heart and soul, to find something elusive, to make something unsubstantial become palpable...to use the crudest of tools to make magic. Every year I start again, from scratch, trying to reach the moon, like the proverbial stretch of the puppet's grasp, ever so slightly always out of reach...I am full of wild ideas and I am hoping at least some of them come true!
Us cats are staying warm and dry!
I lined up all my antique candle shades on the mantle and lit them up with fairy lights!  I’m leaving them up all year!

I’ve always loved old distressed unpainted wood but I find myself going through a phase of loving old painted furniture…so I had to bring this home from @thegrandecollectivevintage and I’m re-doing my bedroom now!  It works so well with the Scottish shepherdess Staffordshire figure I brought home from Edinburgh!

It’s always a trip to the past when I start  cleaning up and organizing my attic storage space… unearthed this self portrait I did in 1967 when I was 16.  Those eyes just look right through the decades and my original self speaks to me.  I remember that solitary girl trying to find her place in the world.

Laying out sweet materials for Valentines! Our shop is re-opening on the first Saturday and Sunday of February 4-5 for a Valentines Open House.  We are making a charming variety of cards, boxes, banners, and gifts of love and affection!

I’ve got dozens of Godeys books in my library…. From the 1850’s through the 1870’s.  They offer the most engrossing portrait of those times.  The engravings are astonishing- the elaborate decorative clothing and hairstyles - and the hand craft projects presented reached into the fantastical!  A case in point are these two designs for toothpick holders…. Made from lobster claws!  I am endlessly fascinated and inspired by the wild novelty of designs that came out of the Victorian brain!

Now that my spring show is over I’m turning my hand to de-constructing and repairing my Shadow Dancer! Stay tuned!

It’s been a nerve wracking process of getting her correctly wired and pinned together!  I’ve had to take her all apart several times - as well as the ghostly puppeteers- and install alot of hidden springs!
Still a bit of work to do… but she is coming back to life!  I made this shadow theatre in 2001 as a very personal attempt to show the world what my vision was of the Theatre of Dreams.

These are early sketches I did when I was first imagining my Theatre of Dreams Shadow Puppet in 2001.  The idea was always somewhere in my brain ….but one time I went to the flea market and came home with three tiny pairs of antique hands.  The entire theatre materialized around those hands and I immediately started to draw!  In the next month all the objects I needed came to me - the gothic Victorian frame, the antique grey silk crepe that swathes the ghostly puppeteers, the shredded pink silk curtains…..
The ghostly puppeteers stand behind the theatre scrim and inside a half dome made of cardboard.  I painted a twilight sky full of clouds and on one side a crescent moon.

The theatre of my dreams comes alive in my shadow dancer with her ghostly puppeteers!  I constructed this fantastical mechanical theatre out of all antiques - including the tinker toy wind up motor!  It was truly a labor of love and continues to delight customers who wander in to my little shop!

Last post about the Shadow Theatre!  The silk scrim which veils the dancer is printed with a fantastical image.  This image is from a Masonic apron which hangs in my studio and dates from about 1860.  All the mythological figures and mysterious symbols are exactly what I wanted on the unlit screen.

I found one of the original slate blackboards from the old Port Costa school house - it weighs a ton!  I mounted it to the wall and I keep my favorite quotes there.  One of my areas of collecting is early antique lighting - that’s an 1850’s astral lamp in the center.  All my lamps are functional and run on lamp oil.  When there is a power outage - my house it lit up!

The old slate chaulkboard is from 1910.  I keep my favorite quotes on it.
“I sell the shadow to support the substance” was found on the carte d’visite of Sojourner Truth.  In her case, she was selling the “shadow” of her own self - an early photographic image - to support her travels in her quest for equality.  I love the quote but it has another meaning to me - as an artist, I sell the shadow - the elusive remains of my imagination - in order to support myself.

It’s Summer Soltice and a mystical day of turning in my world.  It connects me to my mother, whose birthday it is, and to several other landmarks in my personal history, some sad and some joyful.  But it’s always a day of slowing down and feeling deeply grateful, and a day of re-setting my compass for the rest of the year.  I’ll be on the lookout tonight for that sliver of brilliance which is the new moon!

It is Saturday night at 11 pm…and I sit thinking about my day.  I have my glass of wine and a plate with a few crackers and some cheese.  This is the sweetest spot of the day.  It has been a dizzying week of work.  When I stop and have a moment to think… I wonder what happiness is - where is it buried in my day?  It is embedded, just as my deep sadness is, as well as all of my hopes, in the busy-ness of the day.  In making prototypes for next month, wrapping up orders,  glueing together boxes, re-stocking paper bags … it is in all of the absorbing as well as petty details of my creative work - because every detail of it, including sweeping the floors, is an act of meaning, an act of intention, an act of devotion.  An act of continuous construction and an act of faith.  Like I am building, brick by brick, a cathedral of some sort to the imagination itself.
And I have to constantly keep building it in one way or another, or it will fall into ashes and dust.  It is the act itself which keeps its breath alive.

I sometimes get asked - what’s a limited edition??!! I really don’t like that phrase cuz it reminds me of the faux “collectibles” market of junk in the 1970’s, now forever donated to thrift stores after being left behind at the estate sale!  But I use it to describe designs that we make which we truly cannot replicate, or manufacture, because they use a material or part that we cannot get anymore.  Such is the case with these cotton swans that we added vintage cream felt wings and tails!  A limited edition item is almost always under 100 pieces, and quite labor intensive.  We usually split the inventory 50/50 between the shop and the website. These mica flittered swans will be sailing into the shop in early November!

ROUTINE & RITUAL: I've been thinking alot this New Years about how to slow down a bit and enjoy my days. I've had a very tumultuous life in many ways and I usually find routines to be deadening. I've spent most of my life throwing myself into a spinning chaos of creative projects and have usually found the daily routines of cooking, cleaning up, sweeping - all that general upkeep - to be annoying. All that stress and chaos has the ability to distract me from darker stuff. But as I've gotten older I am looking at routine a little differently - I am looking at ways to turn routines into ritual. I just have to find the essential meaning in an everyday act, and give it all of its due respect.
A ritual never looses its pleasure or signifigance. A routine does. Sitting in bed and drinking my coffee every morning, and feeling how lucky I am. - that is a ritual. Clearing off my desk and setting out my pens and pencils, my sketchbooks, or setting up my shop for an open house is a ritual of deep intention and meaning. Sweeping the floor in a thorough way can give me satisfaction if done well. 
This year I am going to try to slow down enough to imbue the simple chores of life with a bit of magic and meaning and turn them into ritual.
Purpose. attention. gratitude. those things can turn a chore into a ritual.
It’s a joy to spend a few days off - just fluffing up the house and lingering in the beautiful aftermath of Christmas!
